      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Accessing `data[i+1]` while inside the loop is indeed a common culprit for the \"index out of range\" error. \n\nOne way to handle this is to use a `while` loop instead of a `for` loop, and use the `i` variable to keep track of the current index. This way, you can control the increment of the index and avoid trying to access `data[i+1]` when `i` is already at the end of the list.\n\nHere's an example:\n```python\ndata = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\ni = 0\nwhile i < len(data) - 1:\n    print(data[i])\n    i += 1\n```\nAlternatively, you can use the `range` function to generate indices up to the second-to-last element of the list, which avoids the indexing issue altogether:\n```python\ndata = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\nfor i in range(len(data) - 1):\n    print(data[i])\n```\nBoth of these approaches should help you avoid the \"index out of range\" error when trying to access the next element in the list.",
